[In the 1997 postings on polio in Ethiopia (referenced above), an initial
report of an outbreak was further defined as referring to "old cases" of
polio that were being publicized preceding a vaccination campaign in order
to increase awareness. In the present reports included above there is one
recent laboratory-confirmed case mentioned, an additional 5 cases with
onset greater than 2 months preceding detection (in children less than 5
years of age, so presumably cases with onset between 2 months and 59 months
before the announcement), and another report of 524 suspected cases
reported during a polio campaign (presumably during a polio vaccination
campaign conducted in the preceding month).
As part of the polio eradication effort, there is an intensification of
disease surveillance activities looking for cases of acute flaccid
paralysis (AFP) of which one etiology is poliovirus. An indicator of a good
disease surveillance system is considered to be detection of a baseline
rate of non-polio AFP of 1 per 100 000 population (less than 15 years of age).
(For more information on surveillance indicators recommended in the
poliomyelitis eradication program see:
<http://www.who.int/vaccines-surveillance/deseasedesc/RSS_polio.htm#PrincipleUseDataDecMak>).
According to the WHO polio eradication website
(<http://www.who.int/vaccines/casecount/afpextractnew.cfm>) Ethiopia has
reported (to date in 2001) 297 cases of AFP, with a non-polio AFP rate of
1.2; 56 per cent of reported AFP cases had adequate laboratory specimens
collected and sent for confirmation, with a total of one confirmed case of
wild poliovirus to date.
The above news articles suggest that further AFP cases have been identified
in the past month, showing further improvements in disease surveillance
activities. More information on the current polio situation in Ethiopia
would be appreciated. - Mod.MPP
